sql:
SELECT researcher_id, COUNT(test_id) AS total_tests
FROM granger_causality_tests
GROUP BY researcher_id;

external_knowledge:
External knowledge to enhance clarity:
- Assumption that "most frequently accessed" is inferred from the highest access counts; 
- Reliability score refers to the trustworthiness of the data source, with higher scores indicating more reliable data; 
- The query ranks indicators by access counts in descending order, so the top 5 are those with the highest access counts.

sql:
SELECT researcher_id, COUNT(*) AS number_of_papers
FROM research_papers
GROUP BY researcher_id;

SELECT index_name, last_updated
FROM stock_market_indexes
ORDER BY last_updated DESC;

SELECT AVG(reliability_score) AS average_reliability_score
FROM (
    SELECT reliability_score FROM economic_indicators
    UNION ALL
    SELECT reliability_score FROM stock_market_indexes
) AS combined_reliability_scores;

SELECT date, value
FROM data_series_values
WHERE reliability_score > 7;
